# Pure Function Extraction

When implementing or refactoring TypeScript in `src/`, prefer small pure helpers over logic embedded in route handlers, hooks, or service functions.

## Extract when logic is

- deterministic (same input → same output)
- free of network, filesystem, database, environment, or clock access
- reusable across routes, modules, or UI layers
- hard to test because it sits behind mocks

## Keep inline when logic is

- a one-off glue call with no meaningful behaviour to test
- tightly coupled to a single component render
- extracting would add indirection without improving clarity

## Placement

- Colocate pure helpers with their feature, e.g. `src/lib/rag/search-utils.ts`
- Use a `*-utils.ts` suffix for pure helper modules
- Keep IO orchestration in the main module, e.g. `search.ts` calls Supabase; `search-utils.ts` merges ranks

## Examples from this repo

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — pure helper, easy to unit test
// src/lib/rag/search-utils.ts
export function mergeWithRrf(vectorResults, keywordResults) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — route/module orchestrates IO only
export async function searchDocuments(query: string) {
  const embedding = await embedTexts([query]);
  const vectorResults = await matchChunksVector(embedding);
  return mergeWithRrf(vectorResults, keywordResults);
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ AVOID — ranking logic buried inside an async DB function
export async function searchDocuments(query: string) {
  const vectorResults = await matchChunksVector(...);
  const merged = new Map();
  vectorResults.forEach((result, rank) => { ... }); // extract this
}
```

## Refactor trigger

If you need more than one mock to test business logic, extract the logic into a pure helper first, then test the helper directly.
